The White House Office of the Press Secretary released a joint statement by President Barack Obama and Prime Minister Justin Trudeau on climate, energy, and Arctic leadership. The leaders emphasize their commitment to combatting climate change and advancing clean growth. They vow to play a leadership role in the low-carbon global economy, protect the rights of Indigenous peoples, and cooperate closely with Mexico on climate and energy action. They also pledge to implement the Paris Agreement, work with developing countries to assist in implementing their climate commitments, and promote the use of carbon markets. Both countries commit to reducing methane emissions from the oil and gas sector, and to regulate existing sources of methane emissions. They also endorse the World Bank's Zero Routine Flaring by 2030 Initiative and commit to reducing use and emissions of hydrofluorocarbons. The leaders affirm their commitment to reducing emissions from vehicles and major projects, and to addressing the intersection of climate change and security. They pledge to cooperate on clean energy development and to strengthen the security and resilience of the North American electricity grid. Lastly, they outline a shared Arctic leadership model that includes conserving Arctic biodiversity, incorporating Indigenous science and traditional knowledge into decision-making, building a sustainable Arctic economy, supporting strong Arctic communities, and promoting scientific research in the region.